1
00:00:37,038 --> 00:00:39,040
[♪♪♪]

2
00:00:57,725 --> 00:01:00,269
MAN 1 [ON RADIO]:
<i>Go for comms, Delta Two. Sitrep.</i>

3
00:01:01,270 --> 00:01:04,732
MAN 2 [ON RADIO]: <i>Ain't looking good, LT.
Soup sandwich in here.</i>

4
00:01:04,815 --> 00:01:07,109
<i>Four hostages down.</i>

5
00:01:09,028 --> 00:01:12,323
<i>Looks like they interrogated them
and dumped the bodies here.</i>

6
00:01:12,406 --> 00:01:14,617
MAN 1:
<i>Echo Two, give me a sitrep.</i>

7
00:01:14,700 --> 00:01:17,995
MAN 3 [ON RADIO]:
<i>No sign of alpha target. Moving location.</i>

8
00:01:21,082 --> 00:01:23,292
[MAN SPEAKING IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE]

9
00:01:32,802 --> 00:01:34,804
[♪♪♪]

10
00:01:44,438 --> 00:01:46,649
[MEN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

11
00:01:46,732 --> 00:01:49,735
Contact, building two, ground floor.

12
00:01:51,988 --> 00:01:54,240
[MEN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

13
00:01:55,908 --> 00:01:57,368
[GUNFIRE]

14
00:02:06,877 --> 00:02:08,421
MAN 1:
<i>Bravo Six, hold on breach.</i>

15
00:02:12,717 --> 00:02:14,385
RAY:
<i>Roger that. Breaching now.</i>

16
00:02:18,806 --> 00:02:21,767
MAN 1: <i>Delta, Echo, hustle, hustle.
Double time. Bravo's on location.</i>

17
00:02:21,851 --> 00:02:24,854
<i>Goddamn it, Bravo Six,
I said, hold on breach!</i>

18
00:02:31,152 --> 00:02:32,987
[♪♪♪]

19
00:03:12,902 --> 00:03:13,903
Drop your gun.

20
00:03:15,029 --> 00:03:17,823
I said, drop your gun!

21
00:03:26,040 --> 00:03:27,500
RAY:
All right.

22
00:03:28,918 --> 00:03:29,835
Take it easy.

23
00:03:32,588 --> 00:03:34,632
What do you want?

24
00:03:34,715 --> 00:03:37,802
-Helicopter. Now!
MAN 1: <i>On location. Building two.</i>

25
00:03:37,885 --> 00:03:40,513
And tell them to back off!

26
00:03:40,596 --> 00:03:43,724
Alpha One, stand down.
We got this situation handled.

27
00:03:43,808 --> 00:03:45,059
MAN 1:
<i>Roger that. Holding.</i>

28
00:03:46,519 --> 00:03:49,313
If you want a helicopter,
you gotta give me a phone.

29
00:03:50,523 --> 00:03:52,191
- There.
- Where?

30
00:03:53,234 --> 00:03:54,610
There.

31
00:04:08,749 --> 00:04:12,002
MAN 1:
<i>Bravo Six in sight. Alpha target secure.</i>

32
00:04:12,086 --> 00:04:14,088
[♪♪♪]

33
00:04:23,973 --> 00:04:26,684
Why do these flights always feel so long?

34
00:04:30,771 --> 00:04:32,648
That's what we fight for, guys.

35
00:04:32,731 --> 00:04:34,692
Oh, man, I need to get home.

36
00:04:34,775 --> 00:04:37,611
No mission too difficult,
no sacrifice too great!

37
00:04:37,695 --> 00:04:39,572
ALL:
Duty first!

38
00:04:41,407 --> 00:04:43,826
MAN:
That's it! To the hangar.

39
00:04:46,745 --> 00:04:49,457
Boss, I'll take that for you.

40
00:04:56,589 --> 00:04:58,591
[♪♪♪]

41
00:05:30,581 --> 00:05:31,790
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

42
00:05:58,067 --> 00:06:00,236
You think someday...

43
00:06:00,319 --> 00:06:04,657
just once, you could come back
in the same shape you left?

44
00:06:06,033 --> 00:06:07,952
RAY:
You don't like my scars?

45
00:06:11,038 --> 00:06:13,541
I don't mind the scars.

46
00:06:14,583 --> 00:06:16,585
I just don't like the stories they tell.

47
00:06:19,255 --> 00:06:22,508
You know the funny thing
about the stories they tell?

48
00:06:22,591 --> 00:06:25,010
Is they all end the same.

49
00:06:25,094 --> 00:06:27,263
I always come home.

50
00:06:28,389 --> 00:06:30,224
Just saying,

51
00:06:30,307 --> 00:06:32,184
at some point,

52
00:06:32,268 --> 00:06:34,770
your body can't do this forever.

53
00:06:39,483 --> 00:06:42,695
Are you questioning
what my body can and can't do?

54
00:06:46,949 --> 00:06:50,578
Well, maybe I just need
a little reeducation.

55
00:07:26,238 --> 00:07:28,490
[FLOORBOARDS CREAKING]

56
00:07:31,243 --> 00:07:32,286
Baby?

57
00:07:38,083 --> 00:07:39,585
[♪♪♪]

58
00:07:41,253 --> 00:07:42,796
[YELLING]

59
00:08:06,904 --> 00:08:08,364
Oh, shit.

60
00:08:13,035 --> 00:08:14,495
Gina.

61
00:08:18,165 --> 00:08:19,667
What's your problem?

62
00:08:38,644 --> 00:08:40,229
[IN DISTORTED VOICE]
You all right, mate?

63
00:08:43,649 --> 00:08:45,275
Yeah.

64
00:08:54,159 --> 00:08:55,911
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

65
00:09:17,516 --> 00:09:19,518
[STATIC CRACKLES ON RADIO]

66
00:09:21,311 --> 00:09:24,648
[TALKING HEADS' "PSYCHO KILLER" PLAYING]

67
00:09:32,823 --> 00:09:36,577
♪ <i>I can't seem to face up to the facts</i> ♪

68
00:09:36,660 --> 00:09:40,456
♪ <i>I'm tense and nervous and I can't relax</i> ♪

69
00:09:40,539 --> 00:09:44,585
♪ <i>I can't sleep 'cause my bed's on fire</i> ♪

70
00:09:44,668 --> 00:09:48,130
♪ <i>Don't touch me, I'm a real live wire</i> ♪

71
00:09:48,922 --> 00:09:50,841
♪ <i>Psycho killer ♪</i>

72
00:09:50,924 --> 00:09:52,176
♪ <i>Qu'est-ce que c'est?</i> ♪

73
00:09:52,259 --> 00:09:56,764
♪ <i>Fa-fa-fa-fa-fa-fa-fa-fa-fa-far better</i> ♪♪

74
00:09:57,389 --> 00:09:58,432
Never gets old.

75
00:09:59,767 --> 00:10:02,394
- Who are you?
- Who am I?

76
00:10:02,478 --> 00:10:05,063
I'm the bloke that ruined your vacation.

77
00:10:07,941 --> 00:10:09,568
Name's Martin Axe.

78
00:10:10,569 --> 00:10:14,198
So that's one for you. Now one for me.

79
00:10:14,281 --> 00:10:17,785
Who tipped you off
about the hostages in Mombasa?

80
00:10:21,538 --> 00:10:24,124
Right, yeah. I thought you might clam up.

81
00:10:24,208 --> 00:10:26,293
That's why I brought
a little extra motivation.

82
00:10:26,376 --> 00:10:27,669
[WHISTLES]

83
00:10:31,548 --> 00:10:32,883
[GAS HISSING]

84
00:10:35,344 --> 00:10:36,428
Look who it is.

85
00:10:37,179 --> 00:10:38,430
[AXE GIGGLES]

86
00:10:39,306 --> 00:10:40,766
[♪♪♪]

87
00:10:41,600 --> 00:10:44,061
- Who's that?
- Gina.

88
00:10:48,148 --> 00:10:48,982
AXE:
Hey.

89
00:10:50,275 --> 00:10:51,985
She has nothing to do with this.

90
00:10:53,362 --> 00:10:55,906
Once again, then. Who tipped you off?

91
00:10:55,989 --> 00:11:00,369
I don't know, man. That's not my job.
I go where they point me.

92
00:11:11,380 --> 00:11:13,799
Can she handle all six inches?

93
00:11:13,882 --> 00:11:16,593
Why am I asking you, eh? Heh.

94
00:11:17,594 --> 00:11:19,179
Hey, look at me.

95
00:11:20,222 --> 00:11:21,723
Look at me!

96
00:11:21,807 --> 00:11:25,060
I don't... I can't answer
because I don't know.

97
00:11:25,143 --> 00:11:27,187
If I knew, I would tell you!

98
00:11:27,271 --> 00:11:29,398
I don't know!

99
00:11:29,481 --> 00:11:31,692
You could ask me anything, anything else,

100
00:11:31,775 --> 00:11:34,236
but this I can't tell you
because I don't know.

101
00:11:42,744 --> 00:11:44,454
Yeah, I believe you.

102
00:11:46,665 --> 00:11:49,042
Ray. Ray. Ray.

103
00:11:52,546 --> 00:11:54,464
- Ray.
- It's gonna be okay.

104
00:12:01,138 --> 00:12:02,139
Bad news, baby.

105
00:12:03,348 --> 00:12:04,600
It's not gonna be okay.

106
00:12:07,436 --> 00:12:09,313
-No! No!
GINA: No, no, no.

107
00:12:09,396 --> 00:12:10,898
[BOLT GUN WHOOSHES]

108
00:12:37,132 --> 00:12:38,884
Oh, you're nothing.

109
00:12:39,885 --> 00:12:42,471
You don't even exist anymore.

110
00:12:42,554 --> 00:12:46,058
I swear, I will find you and end you!

111
00:12:46,141 --> 00:12:48,268
[♪♪♪]

112
00:12:48,977 --> 00:12:53,649
You should kill me now
because you won't have a second chance.

113
00:12:53,732 --> 00:12:55,943
I promise you.

114
00:12:58,737 --> 00:13:00,155
[MUSIC SHUTS OFF]

115
00:13:00,864 --> 00:13:01,990
AXE:
Thanks for the advice.

116
00:13:11,416 --> 00:13:13,418
[♪♪♪]

117
00:13:32,813 --> 00:13:34,815
[EKG FLATLINING]

118
00:13:34,898 --> 00:13:37,693
HARTING:
<i>Commence bioelectrical charge.</i>

119
00:13:39,569 --> 00:13:41,571
<i>Seventy-five percent.</i>

120
00:13:44,449 --> 00:13:45,993
<i>Full cycle.</i>

121
00:13:46,076 --> 00:13:48,078
[EKG BEEPING]

122
00:14:00,465 --> 00:14:04,094
<i>Project Bloodshot procedure log,
transfusion complete.</i>

123
00:14:09,057 --> 00:14:11,643
KT:
Subject awake and is stable.

124
00:14:28,493 --> 00:14:30,162
Hey. Hey, look at me.

125
00:14:30,245 --> 00:14:35,459
Hey, hey, hey, look at me. You're okay.
It's gonna be fine. It's okay.

126
00:14:36,877 --> 00:14:37,878
Where am I?

127
00:15:01,860 --> 00:15:03,278
Awake and cognitive.

128
00:15:03,361 --> 00:15:05,530
This is... This is phenomenal.

129
00:15:07,574 --> 00:15:08,700
RAY:
Do I know you guys?

130
00:15:08,784 --> 00:15:13,205
I don't think so. Welcome to RST,
Rising Spirit Technologies.

131
00:15:13,288 --> 00:15:17,876
I'm Dr. Emil Harting.
This is my facility and my colleague, KT.

132
00:15:18,960 --> 00:15:22,047
- Katie.
- Initials, KT.

133
00:15:22,130 --> 00:15:23,799
Will you look at me, please?

134
00:15:26,510 --> 00:15:30,180
Dilation looks good.
No sign of sub-macular hemorrhaging.

135
00:15:30,263 --> 00:15:32,099
There's no redness. Very clear.

136
00:15:32,182 --> 00:15:35,936
All right, what happened to me?
What am I doing here?

137
00:15:36,019 --> 00:15:38,146
Tell me, do you remember anything?

138
00:15:38,230 --> 00:15:41,858
- Anything's kind of broad, don't you think?
- Of course. Let's keep it simple.

139
00:15:41,942 --> 00:15:45,362
What about your name, rank, serial number?

140
00:15:45,445 --> 00:15:47,155
RAY:
Of course.

141
00:15:48,615 --> 00:15:49,616
My name is...

142
00:15:54,955 --> 00:15:56,957
Rank, serial number?

143
00:15:57,040 --> 00:16:01,378
Yes, your body was donated
by the U.S. military.

144
00:16:02,420 --> 00:16:06,258
- My body?
- It was either us or Arlington, I'm afraid.

145
00:16:08,093 --> 00:16:09,719
Arlington, doc?

146
00:16:10,720 --> 00:16:14,558
I got some scars,
but I'm not ready for the cemetery.

147
00:16:14,641 --> 00:16:18,728
I'm sorry to be the one to tell you this,
but you got yourself killed.

148
00:16:23,984 --> 00:16:25,735
Okay.

149
00:16:26,736 --> 00:16:28,113
I'll play along.

150
00:16:29,114 --> 00:16:31,032
But if I died...

151
00:16:32,033 --> 00:16:34,536
somebody's waiting for me to call them.

152
00:16:34,619 --> 00:16:37,831
Somebody must be waiting for me
to come home.

153
00:16:39,124 --> 00:16:40,792
Uh...

154
00:16:40,876 --> 00:16:42,711
It's difficult for me to tell you this.

155
00:16:42,794 --> 00:16:45,547
More difficult
than telling someone they died?

156
00:16:47,966 --> 00:16:51,928
Well, the military only anonymously
donates remains of soldiers

157
00:16:52,012 --> 00:16:55,140
who weren't claimed by family.

158
00:16:56,391 --> 00:16:57,392
Sorry.

159
00:16:57,475 --> 00:16:59,644
Sometimes you just got to rip off
the Band-Aid.

160
00:16:59,728 --> 00:17:02,522
Helps to get through the pain a bit quicker.

161
00:17:04,733 --> 00:17:07,402
But you don't need a history
to have a future.

162
00:17:07,485 --> 00:17:08,528
Listen to me.

163
00:17:08,612 --> 00:17:12,115
You're the first
we've successfully managed to bring back.

164
00:17:12,199 --> 00:17:13,825
And it has worked beautifully.

165
00:17:14,826 --> 00:17:17,537
You have been given something
that nobody else has.

166
00:17:19,247 --> 00:17:20,916
A second chance.

167
00:17:20,999 --> 00:17:22,626
[♪♪♪]

168
00:17:24,377 --> 00:17:25,795
A second chance.

169
00:17:31,635 --> 00:17:32,469
RAY:
Whoa.

170
00:17:33,803 --> 00:17:36,139
Ain't what I was expecting.

171
00:17:37,933 --> 00:17:39,935
What are we doing out here, doc?

172
00:17:45,023 --> 00:17:49,611
RST focuses on rebuilding the most important
asset in the U.S. military,

173
00:17:49,694 --> 00:17:51,696
soldiers just like yourself.

174
00:17:52,739 --> 00:17:55,617
We are explorers on a new frontier.

175
00:17:55,700 --> 00:17:58,620
We develop everything
from exoskeletal reconstruction,

176
00:17:58,703 --> 00:18:01,122
which makes soldiers faster and stronger,

177
00:18:01,206 --> 00:18:04,167
to neural prosthetics,
which enhance the way they react.

178
00:18:04,251 --> 00:18:06,962
But you, my friend,

179
00:18:07,045 --> 00:18:09,005
you are the proof
that we are leading the way

180
00:18:09,089 --> 00:18:11,675
in the greatest human advancement
of all time.

181
00:18:12,676 --> 00:18:14,302
Come, I'll show you.

182
00:18:26,606 --> 00:18:29,734
-May I?
RAY: Yeah, sure. Ungh!

183
00:18:30,402 --> 00:18:31,736
The hell, doc?

184
00:18:36,825 --> 00:18:38,326
Holy shit.

185
00:18:44,082 --> 00:18:46,167
HARTING:
Let me explain.

186
00:18:46,251 --> 00:18:48,962
If you would place your hand here, please.

187
00:18:50,005 --> 00:18:51,548
Now, look at this.

188
00:18:55,218 --> 00:18:57,429
Now, what the hell are those things?

189
00:18:57,512 --> 00:18:59,264
Biomechanical constructs.

190
00:18:59,347 --> 00:19:01,433
<i>We call them "nanites."</i>

191
00:19:03,685 --> 00:19:05,478
<i>They intuitively enhance your biology.</i>

192
00:19:05,562 --> 00:19:09,482
<i>Most notably, they react very quickly
to catastrophic injury,</i>

193
00:19:09,566 --> 00:19:11,860
<i>rebuilding damaged tissue.</i>

194
00:19:18,325 --> 00:19:19,993
So those are in my blood?

195
00:19:20,076 --> 00:19:21,411
They are your blood.

196
00:19:21,494 --> 00:19:24,247
We had some success applying them
to single organ systems.

197
00:19:24,331 --> 00:19:27,625
We thought it was time
to try a full-body transfusion.

198
00:19:28,626 --> 00:19:29,753
Of course, you did.

199
00:19:29,836 --> 00:19:33,506
And just like our own bodies need calories,
the nanites need their own energy.

200
00:19:33,590 --> 00:19:34,966
And this lab supplies that.

201
00:19:35,050 --> 00:19:38,303
Obviously, the more effort they make,
the more energy they consume.

202
00:19:38,386 --> 00:19:39,387
What's that glow?

203
00:19:39,471 --> 00:19:43,975
That's heat being generated
by the nanites battling malignant cancer,

204
00:19:44,059 --> 00:19:45,477
trying to save that mouse.

205
00:19:49,230 --> 00:19:50,899
The mouse that just died?

206
00:19:50,982 --> 00:19:54,486
Admittedly,
some of the early results were suboptimal.

207
00:19:54,569 --> 00:19:56,613
Maybe we should fast-forward
to the optimal part.

208
00:19:56,696 --> 00:19:58,865
That's you. You're the optimal part.

209
00:19:58,948 --> 00:20:02,452
Because now we have the ability
to recharge when they're running low.

210
00:20:05,789 --> 00:20:07,832
Why can't I remember anything about me?

211
00:20:07,916 --> 00:20:10,919
Because of who you were and what you did.

212
00:20:11,961 --> 00:20:15,715
- Sadly, everything about you is classified.
- And that was all in your past.

213
00:20:15,799 --> 00:20:17,008
This is your future.

214
00:20:17,092 --> 00:20:20,929
Listen, when I was a boy,
I was a tennis champion.

215
00:20:21,012 --> 00:20:25,642
And then when I was 15, I got cancer,
and they took my arm within six months.

216
00:20:25,725 --> 00:20:30,105
Instead of dwelling on what I'd lost,
I chose to focus on who I could become.

217
00:20:31,106 --> 00:20:35,235
And so now, when a soldier loses his arm,
he gets a better one.

218
00:20:40,323 --> 00:20:41,741
This is our rehab facility,

219
00:20:41,825 --> 00:20:45,787
where patients come to test
the limits of their augmentations.

220
00:20:45,870 --> 00:20:48,957
You've already met KT, ex-Navy swimmer.

221
00:20:49,040 --> 00:20:52,544
She was part of a rescue deployment
in Syria during a chemical attack.

222
00:20:52,627 --> 00:20:55,171
One laryngotracheal reconstruction later

223
00:20:55,255 --> 00:20:58,800
and she now breathes
through a clavicle-mounted respirator.

224
00:20:58,883 --> 00:21:00,677
Makes her totally immune to inhalants.

225
00:21:02,095 --> 00:21:05,640
Tibbs here graduated
from Fort Benning, top of his class.

226
00:21:05,723 --> 00:21:08,726
He became one of the Army's
most successful marksmen

227
00:21:08,810 --> 00:21:11,354
until an Iraqi mortar took his sight.

228
00:21:11,438 --> 00:21:14,232
We've since remedied that
with ocular prosthetics.

229
00:21:14,315 --> 00:21:18,862
Gear-mounted camera arrays feed directly
into his optic nerves.

230
00:21:18,945 --> 00:21:21,281
- Which means now he sees...
- Everything.

231
00:21:22,949 --> 00:21:24,284
Welcome to the circus.

232
00:21:24,367 --> 00:21:27,328
And finally, Jimmy Dalton, ex-Navy SEAL.

233
00:21:27,412 --> 00:21:32,333
Jimmy lost both his feet to an Afghan IED,
so we engineered him a new set.

234
00:21:32,417 --> 00:21:35,712
- Part of Team Six. Took out bin Laden.
- You and every other Navy SEAL.

235
00:21:37,797 --> 00:21:39,549
So we're wounded warriors.

236
00:21:39,632 --> 00:21:41,092
Not wounded.

237
00:21:41,176 --> 00:21:44,179
Improved. Enhanced.

238
00:21:44,262 --> 00:21:45,305
[TREADMILL STOPS]

239
00:21:45,388 --> 00:21:46,931
- Sounds cool.
- Yeah.

240
00:21:47,015 --> 00:21:48,141
Yeah.

241
00:21:51,227 --> 00:21:55,440
- Where you going?
- Oh, I'm gonna go back to sleep.

242
00:21:55,523 --> 00:21:58,526
Or maybe I'm just gonna wake up.

243
00:22:01,988 --> 00:22:05,241
- So, what are we supposed to do now?
- I think we just let him recover.

244
00:22:05,325 --> 00:22:07,202
Jimmy, will you walk him
to his room, please?

245
00:22:13,917 --> 00:22:15,877
RAY:
Wow, they spared every expense.

246
00:22:15,960 --> 00:22:19,255
When you're done with your nap,
we'll be downstairs doing our jobs.

247
00:22:19,339 --> 00:22:22,800
- Yeah, I don't even know what my job is.
- You'll find out.

248
00:22:22,884 --> 00:22:26,346
When you're ready, I'll tell you everything.

249
00:22:29,182 --> 00:22:31,184
[♪♪♪]

250
00:22:58,169 --> 00:22:59,087
RAY:
<i>No!</i>

251
00:23:31,369 --> 00:23:33,371
[♪♪♪]

252
00:25:33,241 --> 00:25:35,243
[♪♪♪]

253
00:26:21,956 --> 00:26:23,458
You're up late.

254
00:26:24,500 --> 00:26:26,377
Yeah, I couldn't sleep.

255
00:26:30,381 --> 00:26:34,260
You know, if I was dead yesterday,
I wouldn't be able to sleep either.

256
00:26:34,343 --> 00:26:35,887
Nah, I had a nightmare.

257
00:26:36,888 --> 00:26:38,264
Which doesn't make any sense.

258
00:26:38,347 --> 00:26:41,392
How can you have a nightmare
if you have no memories?

259
00:26:41,476 --> 00:26:43,311
Trust me.

260
00:26:45,688 --> 00:26:49,609
Soon, you'll remember enough
to wish you could forget it again.

261
00:26:54,572 --> 00:26:56,741
That was pretty amazing in there.

262
00:26:56,824 --> 00:26:59,035
A kata underwater.

263
00:26:59,118 --> 00:27:00,578
You know...

264
00:27:03,331 --> 00:27:05,541
we're all damaged goods here.

265
00:27:05,625 --> 00:27:07,543
But this is who I am now.

266
00:27:07,627 --> 00:27:09,378
I've embraced it.

267
00:27:11,672 --> 00:27:14,467
Hey, there's something I want you to have.

268
00:27:19,222 --> 00:27:21,724
I carry it with me all the time.

269
00:27:21,808 --> 00:27:25,061
First time I served on that ship,
I was the only woman there.

270
00:27:25,144 --> 00:27:27,605
Master chief knew that I had nobody, so...

271
00:27:29,357 --> 00:27:32,068
he wanted to make a point that I belong.

272
00:27:41,661 --> 00:27:44,705
I'm sure there's someone out there
who cares about you a great deal.

273
00:27:44,789 --> 00:27:46,833
You just don't know it yet.

274
00:27:49,252 --> 00:27:50,837
I hope so.

275
00:27:51,963 --> 00:27:53,714
You look like you could use a drink.

276
00:27:55,675 --> 00:28:00,346
I already know what I like, so I guess
it's time for you to find out what you like.

277
00:28:00,429 --> 00:28:01,931
Okay, go easy on me.

278
00:28:02,014 --> 00:28:04,392
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

279
00:28:08,229 --> 00:28:10,064
To new beginnings.

280
00:28:13,150 --> 00:28:15,570
[TALKING HEADS' "PSYCHO KILLER"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

281
00:28:21,576 --> 00:28:23,536
-I feel like I've been...
GINA: <i>Ray.</i>

282
00:28:25,121 --> 00:28:27,039
Ray. Ray. Ray.

283
00:28:28,249 --> 00:28:30,084
KT: Are you okay?
<i>- Ray.</i>

284
00:28:31,335 --> 00:28:32,461
Hey.

285
00:28:35,798 --> 00:28:36,716
Gina.

286
00:28:36,799 --> 00:28:38,634
♪ <i>I can't face up to the facts</i> ♪

287
00:28:38,718 --> 00:28:40,094
Name's Martin Axe.

288
00:28:40,177 --> 00:28:42,680
- She has nothing to do with this.
- Who?

289
00:28:43,681 --> 00:28:46,893
RAY: If I knew, I would tell you!
- Look at me.

290
00:28:47,768 --> 00:28:50,688
<i>♪ Psycho killer
Qu'est-ce que c'est? ♪</i>

291
00:28:52,607 --> 00:28:54,567
I will find you!

292
00:28:55,526 --> 00:28:57,153
I need medical in here now!

293
00:28:57,236 --> 00:28:58,779
<i>-Listen to me.</i>
RAY: <i>Kill me now!</i>

294
00:28:59,989 --> 00:29:03,784
Kill me! Because you won't get
a second chance!

295
00:29:05,411 --> 00:29:06,746
AXE:
<i>Thanks for the advice.</i>

296
00:29:09,457 --> 00:29:10,666
Hey. It's okay.

297
00:29:10,750 --> 00:29:12,501
- I'm sorry.
- Listen.

298
00:29:12,585 --> 00:29:15,963
- Whatever it is, it's not worth it.
- You don't understand, KT.

299
00:29:16,047 --> 00:29:19,300
♪ <i>Run, run, run away</i> ♪

300
00:29:19,383 --> 00:29:21,302
♪ <i>Oh, oh</i> ♪

301
00:29:21,385 --> 00:29:23,846
I know why I'm alone.

302
00:29:23,930 --> 00:29:25,640
♪ <i>Qu'est-ce que c'est?</i> ♪♪

303
00:29:28,225 --> 00:29:30,645
[♪♪♪]

304
00:29:38,694 --> 00:29:39,820
HARTING:
Where are you going?

305
00:29:48,371 --> 00:29:51,290
Where are you go...? Can he hear me?
Is the channel open?

306
00:29:52,875 --> 00:29:54,794
Eric, open a channel.

307
00:29:54,877 --> 00:29:56,712
ERIC:
And we're live.

308
00:29:56,796 --> 00:29:58,547
<i>Where are you going?</i>

309
00:30:00,508 --> 00:30:02,343
Doc, how are you talking to me?

310
00:30:02,426 --> 00:30:05,388
You have a billion wireless microprocessors
in your brain.

311
00:30:05,471 --> 00:30:08,808
- I need you to come back here right now.
- I've got unfinished business.

312
00:30:11,060 --> 00:30:13,938
What are you waiting for? Go and get him.

313
00:30:14,021 --> 00:30:16,941
We're your only business.
We are the only people you know.

314
00:30:17,024 --> 00:30:18,401
RAY:
<i>That's what you told me.</i>

315
00:30:18,484 --> 00:30:20,152
<i>But I had a wife.</i>

316
00:30:20,236 --> 00:30:22,613
And he took her from me.

317
00:30:23,948 --> 00:30:27,076
- What are you talking about? Who did?
- Martin Axe.

318
00:30:35,710 --> 00:30:38,087
HARTING:
Eric, get me a terminal window.

319
00:30:42,925 --> 00:30:45,511
ERIC: His nanites are scanning
the global search platforms.

320
00:30:52,351 --> 00:30:53,894
HARTING:
Wait, wait, wait. Hold on a second.

321
00:30:53,978 --> 00:30:57,064
You used my tech and scraped
a criminal database. That is beyond illegal.

322
00:30:57,148 --> 00:31:00,401
-I need you to come back now.
RAY: <i>This isn't about what you need.</i>

323
00:31:00,484 --> 00:31:04,071
- I'm sending Tibbs and Dalton after you.
- They won't stop me.

324
00:31:04,155 --> 00:31:05,906
HARTING:
<i>This is not a hitjob.</i>

325
00:31:05,990 --> 00:31:07,950
<i>It's a salvage operation,</i>

326
00:31:08,034 --> 00:31:10,995
and you are a multibillion-dollar prototype.

327
00:31:11,078 --> 00:31:13,789
- You're my multibillion-dollar prototype.
<i>- Doc.</i>

328
00:31:13,873 --> 00:31:16,625
- I can't just have you...
<i>- Doc! I'm not yours.</i>

329
00:31:16,709 --> 00:31:18,919
<i>Besides, I always come home.</i>

330
00:31:19,003 --> 00:31:21,047
HARTING:
<i>You always come home? What?</i>

331
00:31:21,130 --> 00:31:25,259
Look, we don't know what you're capable of.
We don't even know what you can take yet.

332
00:31:26,802 --> 00:31:28,804
[♪♪♪]

333
00:31:30,389 --> 00:31:34,310
- Time for a live-fire test.
- Hold on. Hold on. Let's just take a minute.

334
00:31:34,393 --> 00:31:36,312
Think about this. You don't have any money.

335
00:31:36,395 --> 00:31:38,689
- You don't have a passport.
- Flying private.

336
00:31:40,608 --> 00:31:43,819
ERIC:
One second. He's...

337
00:31:43,903 --> 00:31:45,905
-I got him at the hangar.
HARTING: The Gulfstream?

338
00:31:45,988 --> 00:31:49,784
No, no, no.
I mean, do you even know how to fly?

339
00:31:49,867 --> 00:31:51,869
RAY:
I'll find a way.

340
00:31:51,952 --> 00:31:53,996
HARTING:
You'll find a way? What does that...?

341
00:32:15,226 --> 00:32:17,520
[♪♪♪]

342
00:32:18,562 --> 00:32:19,563
MAN 1 [ON RADIO]:
<i>All clear.</i>

343
00:32:19,647 --> 00:32:21,273
<i>Time to move.</i>

344
00:32:21,357 --> 00:32:23,400
MAN 2 [ON RADIO]:
<i>All right. Radio it in.</i>

345
00:32:23,484 --> 00:32:24,652
<i>Let's go.</i>

346
00:32:24,735 --> 00:32:26,362
<i>ETA 20 minutes.</i>

347
00:32:45,631 --> 00:32:47,424
HARTING:
So how is he tracking him?

348
00:32:47,508 --> 00:32:52,179
Well, it appears he cross-referenced
every available auto manufacturing database

349
00:32:52,263 --> 00:32:55,516
with live GPS data
to identify all the cars in the area.

350
00:32:55,599 --> 00:33:00,354
And then he pinged them one at a time,
all 9000 of them.

351
00:33:01,355 --> 00:33:04,775
- Why?
- To find the five moving in a convoy.

352
00:33:43,814 --> 00:33:46,734
- What the hell's going on?
- Team One, check ahead.

353
00:34:26,273 --> 00:34:28,192
Was that on purpose?

354
00:34:28,275 --> 00:34:30,569
MAN 1: It's blocked.
- Really?

355
00:34:30,653 --> 00:34:32,321
Guys, was that on purpose?

356
00:34:32,404 --> 00:34:36,075
Team Two, take a look.
See if we can push through.

357
00:34:40,955 --> 00:34:41,830
MAN 2:
Flour.

358
00:35:07,856 --> 00:35:09,358
Team One's down.

359
00:35:09,441 --> 00:35:10,943
What about the truck driver?

360
00:35:11,026 --> 00:35:12,695
Driver is...

361
00:35:14,613 --> 00:35:15,489
He's gone.

362
00:35:15,572 --> 00:35:18,117
- Dead?
- No, gone. He's not here.

363
00:35:24,790 --> 00:35:26,834
Oh, that's not good.

364
00:35:40,973 --> 00:35:42,933
[ENGINE SPUTTERING]

365
00:35:43,017 --> 00:35:44,893
MAN 3:
He's down, boss.

366
00:35:52,484 --> 00:35:53,527
[ENGINE SPUTTERS]

367
00:35:53,610 --> 00:35:56,238
-Thermite. Engine's gone.
AXE: This is not good.

368
00:35:56,322 --> 00:35:58,365
All teams, full sweep. Eyes on everything.

369
00:35:58,449 --> 00:36:01,118
-See if there are any more out there.
AXE: We gotta get out of here.

370
00:36:01,201 --> 00:36:03,162
Sit down. My men will handle it.

371
00:36:10,336 --> 00:36:12,463
AXE:
No, no, no, guys. You're not listening!

372
00:36:12,546 --> 00:36:16,759
- I need to get out of this car now!
- First, we sweep, then we switch cars!

373
00:36:30,606 --> 00:36:32,608
Let's take their car.

374
00:36:34,526 --> 00:36:35,402
Oh, man.

375
00:36:36,487 --> 00:36:38,739
[♪♪♪]

376
00:37:09,770 --> 00:37:11,146
[MAN YELLS]

377
00:37:12,314 --> 00:37:13,440
Wait, what's that?

378
00:37:24,243 --> 00:37:25,744
Oh, man, it is him.

379
00:37:25,828 --> 00:37:28,330
Shit. Come on, come on, come on.

380
00:37:29,456 --> 00:37:30,791
<i>- What?</i>
- He's here!

381
00:37:30,874 --> 00:37:32,835
They finished it,
and he's right bloody here!

382
00:37:32,918 --> 00:37:35,421
<i>We all knew
he wasn't gonna let us walk away.</i>

383
00:37:43,303 --> 00:37:46,098
<i>Just let the professionals
we hired handle it.</i>

384
00:37:46,181 --> 00:37:49,059
Oh, sure. Small problem, eh? Your guys suck!

385
00:37:56,316 --> 00:37:58,610
<i>Check on Wigans.
See where he is with that thing.</i>

386
00:37:58,694 --> 00:38:00,237
<i>Find out how much longer.</i>

387
00:38:00,320 --> 00:38:02,448
No, no, no. Don't hang up. Don't... Oh!

388
00:38:02,531 --> 00:38:04,032
I'm screwed!

389
00:38:09,580 --> 00:38:11,790
MAN 1: You see him?
MAN 2: He's in the trailer.

390
00:38:13,041 --> 00:38:14,334
Fire!

391
00:38:23,886 --> 00:38:26,013
Cease fire!

392
00:39:55,310 --> 00:39:57,312
Bugger me.

393
00:39:58,105 --> 00:40:00,941
Shh, shh. Listen.

394
00:40:03,402 --> 00:40:05,737
AXE: He can't get in, can he?
- Not a chance.

395
00:40:16,623 --> 00:40:18,000
[LOCKS CLICK]

396
00:40:40,105 --> 00:40:41,273
Shit.

397
00:41:14,598 --> 00:41:18,852
AXE [DISTORTED]: Don't, please.
Whatever Harting told you, it's not true.

398
00:41:18,935 --> 00:41:22,105
No, wait. Don't. You don't understand.

399
00:41:22,189 --> 00:41:24,483
He's lying to you. I can help you.

400
00:41:24,566 --> 00:41:26,109
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
You're making a mistake.

401
00:41:26,193 --> 00:41:27,903
Thanks for the advice.

402
00:41:27,986 --> 00:41:30,113
No!

403
00:41:45,003 --> 00:41:46,963
TIBBS:
It's about time.

404
00:41:53,804 --> 00:41:54,805
Jesus.

405
00:41:56,139 --> 00:41:57,974
Look what they did to him.

406
00:42:01,353 --> 00:42:04,439
DALTON:
Gotta hand it to him. The guy does damage.

407
00:42:13,115 --> 00:42:15,701
Are you okay? How you feeling?

408
00:42:18,704 --> 00:42:21,665
I just saw the man who murdered my wife.

409
00:42:22,958 --> 00:42:27,379
Looked him dead in the eyes and...
And killed him.

410
00:42:32,092 --> 00:42:35,053
It won't change a thing
because, no matter what,

411
00:42:35,137 --> 00:42:36,972
my wife isn't coming back.

412
00:42:38,056 --> 00:42:40,976
Makes you wonder if it's all worth it.

413
00:42:41,059 --> 00:42:42,728
Yeah, well, I'm done.

414
00:42:42,811 --> 00:42:44,730
Yeah, I'm done too.

415
00:42:45,689 --> 00:42:47,149
[CLEARS THROAT]

416
00:42:47,232 --> 00:42:50,986
- What does that mean?
- She means we're all tired, bub.

417
00:42:52,028 --> 00:42:54,156
Gotta get you back to RST,
get you plugged in.

418
00:42:54,239 --> 00:42:56,032
Let's go.

419
00:43:00,203 --> 00:43:04,416
No one needed to come collect me.
I told Harting I'd come back.

420
00:43:04,499 --> 00:43:07,544
He sent us to make sure
you get back in one piece.

421
00:43:07,627 --> 00:43:09,212
Looks like we were almost late.

422
00:43:12,966 --> 00:43:14,968
[♪♪♪]

423
00:43:28,190 --> 00:43:29,483
What are you doing here, Dal...?

424
00:43:29,566 --> 00:43:30,859
[MACHINE WHIRS]

425
00:43:34,196 --> 00:43:35,238
That's right.

426
00:43:36,239 --> 00:43:38,241
You can't talk.

427
00:43:39,409 --> 00:43:40,577
Truth is...

428
00:43:43,997 --> 00:43:46,166
you aren't at the wheel of your own body.

429
00:43:48,919 --> 00:43:53,965
We just shoved you aside to watch
as we shut down your motor functions.

430
00:43:55,300 --> 00:43:56,676
Look at you.

431
00:43:59,638 --> 00:44:01,139
So angry.

432
00:44:01,223 --> 00:44:03,225
So driven.

433
00:44:04,309 --> 00:44:05,435
[DALTON CHUCKLES]

434
00:44:05,936 --> 00:44:07,729
You think you're the good guy?

435
00:44:08,730 --> 00:44:10,273
That's a goddamn joke.

436
00:44:14,861 --> 00:44:19,366
You're an exhausting shit bird
with a revenge button we keep pushing.

437
00:44:20,367 --> 00:44:23,578
Much as I hate babysitting you...

438
00:44:24,871 --> 00:44:26,957
cleaning up after you,

439
00:44:27,040 --> 00:44:28,959
this little moment...

440
00:44:29,960 --> 00:44:34,047
this small part right here,
makes it all worthwhile.

441
00:44:40,428 --> 00:44:42,138
Gina.

442
00:44:44,224 --> 00:44:46,434
Sweet Gina.

443
00:44:49,563 --> 00:44:51,565
You really believe she's dead.

444
00:44:52,732 --> 00:44:57,404
Every goddamn time.

445
00:44:57,988 --> 00:44:59,239
[♪♪♪]

446
00:44:59,322 --> 00:45:00,907
There it is.

447
00:45:01,908 --> 00:45:03,201
That look.

448
00:45:04,536 --> 00:45:07,205
The dumb-ass catches on too late.

449
00:45:08,206 --> 00:45:11,126
Well, I may be an asshole,
but you're the toy soldier.

450
00:45:11,209 --> 00:45:14,546
We wind you up,
point you at the next victim,

451
00:45:14,629 --> 00:45:17,465
put you back in here,
and then push this button.

452
00:45:23,013 --> 00:45:24,931
Ready to forget?

453
00:45:30,395 --> 00:45:32,898
Told you I'd tell you everything.

454
00:45:33,857 --> 00:45:36,276
[MACHINE WHIRRING]

455
00:46:42,509 --> 00:46:44,511
[♪♪♪]

456
00:46:54,854 --> 00:46:56,564
<i>Drop your gun.</i>

457
00:47:31,516 --> 00:47:33,935
[DISTORTED SHOUTING OVER SPEAKERS]

458
00:47:34,019 --> 00:47:36,479
MAN 1 [OVER SPEAKERS]:
<i>Delta Two. Sitrep.</i>

459
00:47:40,775 --> 00:47:42,193
<i>Thanks for the advice.</i>

460
00:47:50,285 --> 00:47:53,747
MAN 2:
<i>Ain't looking good, LT. LT. Hostages down.</i>

461
00:47:53,830 --> 00:47:57,500
MAN 1: <i>Delta Two. Sitrep.
Delta Two. Sitrep. Go for comms.</i>

462
00:47:57,584 --> 00:47:59,044
HARTING:
And initiate sequence.

463
00:48:01,004 --> 00:48:03,506
MAN 1:
<i>Go for comms, Delta Two. Sitrep.</i>

464
00:48:03,590 --> 00:48:05,633
MAN 2:
<i>Four hostages down.</i>

465
00:48:12,015 --> 00:48:14,225
RAY:
<i>Contact, building two, ground floor.</i>

466
00:48:14,309 --> 00:48:17,270
"I'm done too"? I'm not sure
what you're trying to accomplish.

467
00:48:20,440 --> 00:48:24,110
Why does it matter
if you're gonna wipe his memory again?

468
00:48:24,194 --> 00:48:26,905
HARTING:
It's not him I'm worried about. It's you.

469
00:48:26,988 --> 00:48:29,491
Everything we do here specifically
serves a purpose.

470
00:48:29,574 --> 00:48:31,326
The training, the alcohol, the nightmare.

471
00:48:31,409 --> 00:48:33,828
- I know the script, Harting.
- Well, would you stick to it?

472
00:48:33,912 --> 00:48:37,499
You know that we're compromised. You know
it doesn't work if we don't check every box.

473
00:48:37,582 --> 00:48:41,544
What you're doing to him is not fair
and you know it.

474
00:48:41,628 --> 00:48:43,713
If you don't like it,
you're welcome to leave.

475
00:48:43,797 --> 00:48:49,219
Bullshit. Just like your partners
when they had a problem with it? Like Baris?

476
00:48:51,179 --> 00:48:53,014
You know the moment I walk out that door...

477
00:48:54,599 --> 00:48:56,810
- I can't breathe.
- That's the deal you agreed to.

478
00:48:57,811 --> 00:49:01,481
- That's the choice that you made.
- Well, he deserves to make his.

479
00:49:03,858 --> 00:49:06,361
What he deserves is a military funeral.

480
00:49:06,444 --> 00:49:09,781
- I'm sure that's what he's gonna get.
- Jesus. You're just gonna get rid of him?

481
00:49:12,700 --> 00:49:16,037
- He's a soldier, Harting. You can't do that.
- He's a dead soldier.

482
00:49:16,121 --> 00:49:19,958
He's a dead soldier.
America makes new ones every day.

483
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:24,087
Listen, I will let you in
on a little secret.

484
00:49:25,088 --> 00:49:27,423
This is our last one, okay?

485
00:49:27,507 --> 00:49:28,842
And then we go to market,

486
00:49:28,925 --> 00:49:33,221
with a technology that will redefine warfare
for the highest bidder, and then we're done.

487
00:49:33,304 --> 00:49:35,181
You're still gonna kill innocent people.

